title: For Sale:  Pen Gun NOT NFA
postcontent:
There were about 4000 of these manufactured.  A company named R. J. Braverman created by Bob Braverman designed the gun around 1990.  They were originally marketed by American Derringer Co. as a Model 2 "Pen" Pistol from 1993 to 1994.  They were later marketed by  R. J. Braverman as the Stinger starting in 1995.   I believe they went out of business in 1997.  
 R. J. Braverman Corp. 
88 Parade Road 
Meredith, NH  03253 
1-800-PEN-GUNS

This PenGun is chambered in the .25 Auto caliber. Comes with instructions and holster resembling those designed to carry small Mag Lites. It also has a shirt clip (as you see on pens) mounted with a solid ring around the body.  The gun looks more loke a 2A flashlight and is stainless steel. It is legal since it must be in the "L" position before it will fire.  I have fired the Pen Gun a total of 15 rounds.  It functions as it should.  Obviously unique and rare.  Excellent condition. I completely disassembled, cleaned, and oiled the gun from head to toe when I bought it and it works great!

I have put a total of 40 rounds through it with half being my personal reloads.  The gun will come with 20 rounds of loaded ammo that I reloaded with Hornady A-Max bullets, and a boresnake. Now a little more about the gun.  It of course is sighted for 300 meters, so you have to aim low at 50 and 100 m to hit much.  I have a different front site that can be installed for shooting at 100 yards, but I never got around to it.  The reloads I am selling with it shoot great and give me <2 inch groups off a bag rest at 100 yards.  There are little bumps and scratches on the wood as with most old guns, and a little section of it has some deeper markings.  You can see those in the picture.

Weighing just 9.4 oz (266.5 g) this is Ruger's first entry into the field of tiny, ultra-light defensive pistols.[4] LCP stands for "Lightweight Compact Pistol" and was designed in direct response to customer requests for a compact firearm for use by police as a back-up, and as a defensive handgun for civilian concealed carry needs.

The pistol has a glass-filled nylon frame, a two-finger grip, and a through-hardened blued steel slide. It is similar in appearance to the Kel-Tec P-3AT which weighs 8.3 oz. and uses a similar tension spring for the lightweight hammer, identical locked breech mechanism, and similar takedown method. The main differences are the Glock style extractor and the incorporation of an external slide stop. It is possible to tell if there is a round chambered by looking at the "view hole" next to the extractor

 LaserLyte answers the growing demand for lasers specific to the increasingly popular conceal carry market with the new Ruger LCP Side Mount Laser (CK-AMF). At half the cost of a leading competitor, the CK-AMF fits on the side of the Ruger LCP and the Kel-Tec .380 and .32. Easy to mount on the gun by simply pushing out and replacing the stock pins with the new screws (included). Then push the ergonomic activation button with the index finger and the laser is on target. The CK-AMF design works also as a finger guide that allows for safe trigger control without blocking the laser beam. The programmable laser features a pulse or constant on mode and also has an auto-off function to prevent an unwanted battery drain. The side mounted laser allows the pistol to fit in virtually any nylon pocket holster. The new LaserLyte Ruger LCP Side Mount Laser is compact and light, and foremost – deadly.

This 38 has the "Star" Military ordnance proofs on the cylinder release and main frame along with a "N" on the butt strap.
